[[File:Flag Ceuta.svg|200px|thumb|right|Flag of Ceuta]]
The '''[[flag]] of [[Ceuta]]''' is a black and white [[gyronny]] with a central [[Escutcheon (heraldry)|escutcheon]] displaying the [[Coat of arms of Ceuta|municipal coat of arms]].  (The civil flag omits the escutcheon.)

The gyronny is identical to that of the [[flag of Lisbon]], to commemorate the conquest of the city by the [[Portugal|Portuguese]] in [[Conquest of Ceuta|1415]].<ref name="News1973">{{cite book|author=CBS News|title=The New York Times Encyclopedic Almanac|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EEMKAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=8 July 2013|year=1973|publisher=New York Times, Book & Educational Division.|page=750}}</ref> The city was a part of the [[Portuguese Empire]] until 1640, after which it decided to remain with Spain.<ref name="Drinkwater1786">{{cite book|author=John Drinkwater|title=A History of the Late Siege of Gibraltar: With a Description and Account of that Garrison, from the Earliest Periods|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BeM-AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA95|accessdate=8 July 2013|year=1786|publisher=T. Spilsbury|pages=95–}}</ref> Thus the coat of arms of the city is almost the same as that of the [[Coat of arms of Portugal|Kingdom of Portugal]], showing the seven castles and the five [[Escutcheon (heraldry)|escutcheons]] with [[Argent|silver]] [[Roundel (heraldry)|roundels]].<ref name="McMurdo1889">{{cite book|author=Edward McMurdo|title=The History of Portugal: The history of Portugal from the reign of D. João II to the reign of D. João V|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oGdCAAAAIAAJ|accessdate=8 July 2013|year=1889|page=25}}</ref>

