'''''The Daily Observer''''' is a [[newspaper]] published in [[Bakau]] in [[Banjul]], [[the Gambia]].<ref>"[http://observer.gm/contact Contact Us] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721033054/http://observer.gm/contact |date=2011-07-21 }}." ''The Daily Observer''. Retrieved on 28 February 2009.</ref>

The paper, Gambia's first daily newspaper,<ref name=Williams>Gabriel I. H. Williams, ''Liberia: the heart of darkness'', Trafford Publishing, 2002, p.333{{Self-published inline|certain=yes|date=January 2018}}</ref> was founded by [[Kenneth Best]] in 1990.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}} Best had previously managed another paper called the ''Daily Observer'' in [[Liberia]], until the [[First Liberian Civil War]] caused him to relocate with his family to the Gambia.<ref name=Williams/> In October 1994, following  [[Yahya Jammeh]]'s [[military coup]], Best was expelled from Gambia,<ref>W. Joseph Campbell, ''The emergent independent press in Benin and Côte d'Ivoire'', 1998, p.19</ref> although the newspaper was allowed to continue.

In the early 1990s, the paper ran its ''History Corner'' on its weekend supplement (the Weekend Observer). The Gambian statesman and historian [[Alieu Ebrima Cham Joof]] "pioneered" this column (the ''History Corner'') in 1993 before asking the paper's resident journalist Hassoum Ceesay to take over the column. Ceesay took over it in 1996.<ref>Daily Observer, ''Alh. AE Cham Joof, a great Gambian historian'' (tribute) by Hassoum Ceesay, (Friday, April 15, 2011) [https://archive.is/20130213171328/http://observer.gm/africa/gambia/article/alh-ae-cham-joof-a-great-gambian-historian archive]</ref>
Some of the topics covered during the tenure of Cham Joof included:
:*History Corner with Alhaji A. E Cham Joof, ''Diamond Jubilee of Scouting in The Gambia, Senegambian Scouting Joint Committee Senegalo/Gambian Katibougou old Scouts'' (Weekend Observer, 29–31 March 1995. p. 9 (Gambia))
:*History Corner with Alhaji A. E Cham Joof, ''The History of the Banjul Mosque'', (Weekend Observer, 5–7 May 1995)

==Ebrima Manneh case==
In July 2006, ''Observer'' reporter [[Ebrima Manneh]] was reportedly arrested by state security after attempting to republish a [[BBC News|BBC]] report criticizing Jammeh shortly before an [[African Union]] meeting in [[Banjul]];<ref name="CFP">{{cite web |url=http://www.cpj.org/2009/04/gambia-must-account-for-missing-journalist-ebrima.php |title=Gambia must account for missing journalist Ebrima Manneh |author= |date=14 April 2009 |work= |publisher=[[Committee to Protect Journalists]] |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> his arrest was witnessed by coworkers.<ref name="CFP" /> Though ordered to release Manneh by an [[Economic Community Of West African States]] court, the Gambian government has denied that Manneh is imprisoned.<ref name="AFP" /> According to [[Agence France-Presse|AFP]], an unnamed police source confirmed Manneh's arrest in April 2009, but added he believed Manneh "is no longer alive."<ref name="AFP">{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5izABjky1HY0Bz47DUuc3V3SaNLGQ |title=Missing Gambia journalist is dead: police |author= |date=14 April 2009 |work= |publisher=[[Agence France-Presse|AFP]] |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> [[Amnesty International]] considers Manneh to be a [[prisoner of conscience]] and named him a 2011 "priority case."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amnestyusa.org/individuals-at-risk/priority-cases/gambia-ebrima-manneh/page.do?id=1361052|title=Ebrima Manneh|author=|date=|work=|publisher=[[Amnesty International]]|accessdate=17 April 2011|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110429082908/http://www.amnestyusa.org/individuals-at-risk/priority-cases/gambia-ebrima-manneh/page.do?id=1361052|archivedate=29 April 2011|df=}}</ref> The [[Committee to Protect Journalists]] has also called for his release.<ref name="CFP" />

